{
  "text": "Furthermore, we found very rare pathogens like A. tumefaciens ( Rhizobium radiobacter ) and D. tsuruhatensis . A. tumefaciens is an opportunistic pathogen with a low virulence. It preferably infects chronically debilitated and/or immunocompromised patients with intravascular catheters. In a review of 42 combined cases of Agrobacterium infections, 100% of patients had underlying malignancy or immunocompromising conditions, and 77% had indwelling intravascular devices. The authors suggest that the pathogens' capacity to adhere to silicone surfaces with extracellular slime contributes to the frequent correlation of infection with indwelling devices [CITATION_1] . As PH is not thought to lead to immunodeficiency, it remains unclear why these cases came to an infection.",
